==English==

===Etymology===
French ''[[litière]]'', from ''[[lit]]'', "bed", Latin ''[[lectus]]''; confer Greek ''[[λέκτρον]]''. Had the sense "bed" in very early English, but then came to mean "portable couch", "bedding", "strewn rushes (for animals)", ...

===Noun===
{{en-noun|s|-}}

# (''uncountable'') Collectively, [[item]]s [[discard]]ed on the ground.
# (''countable'') The [[offspring]] of a [[mammal]] [[born]] in one [[birth]].
# (''uncountable'') [[material|Material]] used as [[bedding]] for animals.
# (''countable'') A [[platform]] [[mount]]ed on two [[shaft]]s, or a more elaborate construction, designed to be carried by two (or more) people to [[transport]] one (in luxury models sometimes more) third person(s) or (occasionally in the elaborate version) a cargo, such as a religious idol.

